{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473665"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2686"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2686"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.82,0.02,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102003"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2686"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9693"},{"type":"tags","id":"9694"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3275"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102003"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of episodes of crying and obvious discomfort. These episodes are becoming increasingly frequent, each lasting 10-20 minutes. This morning, the boy had two green vomits and passed a bloody bowel motion. He has no significant medical history, with an uncomplicated gestation and birth. He is up to date with his immunisations and is exclusively breastfed. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears comfortable between the episodes of pain. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. A periumbilical intra-abdominal mass is palpated without causing discomfort. He is wearing an empty nappy and inspection of the anus reveals no abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malrotation of the gut","Intussusception","Gastroenteritis","Haemolytic uraemic syndrome","Milk protein allergy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintussusception\u003C/strong\u003E, a condition where a proximal segment of intestine telescopes into a more distal segment. It typically occurs in infants between 6 - 18 months. The classic triad includes intermittent abdominal pain, vomiting, and bloody stools (often described as \u0027red currant jelly\u0027). The palpable abdominal mass, known as a \u0027sausage-shaped mass\u0027, is a key physical examination finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalrotation of the gut\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in the neonatal period (\u0026lt; 1 month old) with bilious vomiting. While it can cause abdominal pain and vomiting, it doesn\u0027t typically present with bloody stools or a palpable mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause vomiting and diarrhoea, but it wouldn\u0027t explain the intermittent severe pain or the palpable abdominal mass. Bloody stools are also less common in typical gastroenteritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic uraemic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (HUS) typically presents with bloody diarrhoea, but also includes signs of hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, and acute kidney injury. The intermittent pain and palpable mass are not typical of HUS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMilk protein allergy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause gastrointestinal symptoms in infants, including bloody stools. However, it wouldn\u0027t explain the intermittent severe pain or the palpable abdominal mass. Additionally, this infant is exclusively breastfed, making cow\u0027s milk protein allergy less likely (though not impossible if the mother consumes dairy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of intermittent severe abdominal pain, vomiting, bloody stools, and a palpable abdominal mass in an infant of this age strongly points to intussusception as the most likely diagnosis. Prompt diagnosis and management are crucial to prevent complications such as intestinal ischemia and perforation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intussusception is a common cause of acute abdominal pain with intestinal obstruction in infants aged 6 - 18 months.","Classic triad of intussusception includes intermittent abdominal pain, vomiting, and bloody stools (\u0027red currant jelly\u0027).","Palpable abdominal mass is a key physical examination finding in intussusception."],"references":["Marsicovetere P, Ivatury SJ, White B, Holubar SD. Intestinal Intussusception: Etiology, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2017 Feb;30(1):30-39.","Kelley-Quon LI, Arthur LG, Williams RF, Goldin AB, St Peter SD, Beres AL et al. . Management of intussusception in children: A systematic review. J Pediatr Surg. 2021 56(3):587-596."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},